{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e0256a69-303d-4abb-b048-0440fd66ff63","content":"With Microsoft.Testing.Platform on .NET 8, the equivalent command is:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"Category=Integration\" \\\n  -- \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\n**Key changes:**\n\n| VSTest | Microsoft.Testing.Platform |\n|--------|---------------------------|\n| `--logger trx` | `--report-trx` |\n| `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` | `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura` |\n| `--blame-crash` | `--crashdump` |\n| `--blame-hang --blame-hang-timeout 5m` | `--hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m` |\n\n**Required NuGet packages** (add to your test project):\n\n- `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport`\n- `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage`\n- `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump`\n- `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump`\n\nThe `--filter` stays before `--` (it's a `dotnet test` argument). Everything after `--` is forwarded to the test platform host.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"92e0b996-98c6-45e5-bfd0-97fe50093d4b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating their CI test command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest runner) on .NET 8. Let me provide the equivalent command.\n\nKey differences with Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n- `--filter` becomes `--filter`  (same, actually)\n- `--logger trx` becomes `--report-trx`\n- `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` becomes `--collect-coverage` with format specification\n- `--blame-crash` becomes `--crashdump`\n- `--blame-hang` and `--blame-hang-timeout` becomes `--hangdump` with `--hangdump-timeout`\n\n\n- When using Microsoft.Testing.Platform with `dotnet test`, the command syntax changes depending on whether you're using `dotnet test` with the platform enabled or running the test executable directly, and the option passing differs between versions.\n\nFor .NET 8 specifically, I need to clarify the exact command structure: you'd pass dotnet test arguments normally, then use `--` to separate and pass arguments directly to the testing platform, which supports options like `--report-trx` for TRX reporting (requiring the TrxReport extension), `--coverage` with format specification for code coverage (requiring the CodeCoverage extension), and `--crashdump` for crash diagnostics. I'm clarifying how `dotnet test` handles the `--filter` option versus platform-specific arguments passed after `--`, and considering whether to run the test directly or through the test host, then I'll provide a straightforward answer.","outputTokens":1207,"requestId":"BC24:802C:19F9555:1D0E5D1:69FA9055"},"id":"15586c59-78b7-4537-8def-39d228586a06","timestamp":"2026-05-06T00:50:48.189Z","parentId":"3d5c38f6-8048-48a4-bfdd-eb5be1ea1ea8"}
